The paper deals with game theory and graph theory, which are both central topics in computer science. The focus on equilibria and the price of anarchy suggests that cs.GT (Game Theory and Economics) is the most likely sub-category. The use of graphs and the study of local coordination suggest cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) as a likely sub-category. The mention of algorithms and computational complexity suggest cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) and cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) as possible sub-categories. Finally, the study of equilibria and the price of anarchy also suggests cs.LG (Machine Learning) as a possible sub-category.
